context: In 2004, the Swaziland government acknowledged for the first time that it suffered an <b5_0>AIDS crisis<b5_0/>, with <a0_0><b6_0>38.8%<b6_0/><a0_0/> of tested pregnant women infected with HIV (see AIDS in Africa). The then <b7_0>Prime Minister <a1_0>Themba Dlamini<b7_0/><a1_0/> declared a humanitarian crisis due to the combined effect of drought, land degradation, increased poverty, and HIV/AIDS. According to the 2011 UNAIDS Report, Swaziland is close to achieving universal access to HIV/AIDS treatment, defined as <a2_0>80% coverage or greater<a2_0/>. Estimates of treatment coverage range from <a3_0>70% to 80%<a3_0/> of those infected. Life expectancy had fallen from <b8_0>61 years<b8_0/> in 2000 to 32 years in 2009. Tuberculosis is also a significant problem, with an <a4_0>18%<a4_0/> mortality rate. Many patients have a multi-drug resistant strain, and 83% are co-infected with HIV.
